3
00:00:14,840 --> 00:00:15,540
Gravity.

4
00:00:16,900 --> 00:00:18,900
Gravity is a rather special force.

5
00:00:19,100 --> 00:00:19,820
It's unusual.

6
00:00:21,150 --> 00:00:23,780
It has different than electrical forces,

7
00:00:23,780 --> 00:00:24,940
magnetic forces.

8
00:00:25,380 --> 00:00:27,230
And it's connected in some

9
00:00:27,230 --> 00:00:29,080
way with geometric properties of space,

10
00:00:29,080 --> 00:00:29,660
space and

11
00:00:29,660 --> 00:00:29,800
time.

12
00:00:31,019 --> 00:00:33,259
And that connection is of

13
00:00:33,259 --> 00:00:35,500
course the general theory of relativity.

14
00:00:36,640 --> 00:00:38,180
Before we start,

15
00:00:38,180 --> 00:00:41,300
tonight for the most part,

16
00:00:41,420 --> 00:00:42,690
we will not be dealing

17
00:00:42,690 --> 00:00:43,960
with the general theory of relativity.

18
00:00:44,300 --> 00:00:47,960
We will be dealing with gravity

19
00:00:47,960 --> 00:00:51,620
in its oldest and simplest mathematical form.

20
00:00:52,560 --> 00:00:52,860
Well,

21
00:00:52,860 --> 00:00:54,780
perhaps not the oldest and simplest,

22
00:00:54,780 --> 00:00:58,200
but Newtonian gravity.

23
00:00:58,200 --> 00:01:02,360
And going a little beyond what Newton,

24
00:01:02,360 --> 00:01:04,459
certainly nothing that Newton would not

25
00:01:04,459 --> 00:01:06,720
have recognized or couldn't have grasped,

26
00:01:06,720 --> 00:01:08,200
Newton could grasp anything.

27
00:01:08,960 --> 00:01:12,290
But some ways of thinking about it which

28
00:01:12,290 --> 00:01:15,620
will not be found in Newton's actual work.

29
00:01:16,180 --> 00:01:16,860
But still,

30
00:01:16,860 --> 00:01:18,420
Newtonian gravity.

31
00:01:19,100 --> 00:01:21,500
Newtonian gravity set up in a way that,

32
00:01:21,500 --> 00:01:23,580
that is useful for

33
00:01:23,580 --> 00:01:24,840
going on to the general theory.

34
00:01:26,760 --> 00:01:27,360
Okay,

35
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:27,840
let's.

36
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:28,180
Let's go.

37
00:01:31,799 --> 00:01:33,480
begin with Newton's equations.

38
00:01:34,380 --> 00:01:35,580
The first equation,

39
00:01:35,580 --> 00:01:36,400
of course,

40
00:01:36,400 --> 00:01:37,500
is F equals mA.

41
00:01:39,020 --> 00:01:41,100
Force is equal to mass times acceleration.

42
00:01:42,540 --> 00:01:44,960
Let's assume that we have a frame of reference,

43
00:01:45,120 --> 00:01:47,340
a frame of reference that means a set of coordinates

44
00:01:47,340 --> 00:01:48,620
and it's a collection of clocks,

45
00:01:48,940 --> 00:01:52,220
and that frame of reference is what is called

46
00:01:52,220 --> 00:01:53,540
an inertial frame of reference.

47
00:01:54,060 --> 00:01:57,080
An inertial frame of reference simply means

48
00:01:57,080 --> 00:01:58,280
one which,

49
00:01:58,280 --> 00:02:00,420
if there are no objects around

50
00:02:00,420 --> 00:02:02,920
to exert forces on a particular,

51
00:02:03,100 --> 00:02:04,460
let's call it a test object,

52
00:02:05,340 --> 00:02:07,360
a test object is just some object,

53
00:02:07,460 --> 00:02:09,080
a small particle or anything else

54
00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:14,280
that we use to test out the various fields,

55
00:02:14,740 --> 00:02:17,040
force fields that might be acting on it.

56
00:02:17,400 --> 00:02:19,600
An inertial frame is one which,

57
00:02:19,780 --> 00:02:22,600
when there are no objects around to exert forces,

58
00:02:23,540 --> 00:02:26,660
that object will move,

59
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:28,320
with uniform motion,

60
00:02:28,320 --> 00:02:29,580
with no acceleration.

61
00:02:30,600 --> 00:02:33,000
That's the idea of an inertial frame of reference.

62
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:36,080
And so if you're an inertial frame of reference

63
00:02:36,080 --> 00:02:37,390
and you have a pin

64
00:02:37,390 --> 00:02:38,700
and you just let it go,

65
00:02:39,390 --> 00:02:40,240
it stays there.

66
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:41,120
It doesn't move.

67
00:02:41,440 --> 00:02:42,540
If you give it a push,

68
00:02:42,700 --> 00:02:44,760
it will move off with uniform velocity.

69
00:02:46,380 --> 00:02:48,600
That's the idea of an inertial frame of reference.

70
00:02:48,740 --> 00:02:50,480
And in an inertial frame of reference,

71
00:02:52,340 --> 00:02:55,440
the basic Newtonian equation,

72
00:02:57,080 --> 00:02:58,200
equation number one,

73
00:02:58,880 --> 00:03:01,260
I always forget which law is which.

74
00:03:01,720 --> 00:03:03,160
There's Newton's first law,

75
00:03:03,160 --> 00:03:03,740
second law,

76
00:03:03,740 --> 00:03:04,460
and third law.

77
00:03:04,920 --> 00:03:07,100
I never can remember which is which.

78
00:03:07,540 --> 00:03:09,820
But they're all pretty much summarized by

79
00:03:09,820 --> 00:03:14,320
F equals mass times acceleration.

80
00:03:15,140 --> 00:03:16,960
This is a vector equation.

81
00:03:17,220 --> 00:03:19,000
I expect people know what a vector is.

82
00:03:19,500 --> 00:03:21,380
A three vector equation.

83
00:03:21,700 --> 00:03:23,620
We'll come later to four vectors,

84
00:03:24,300 --> 00:03:27,060
where when space and time are united into space,

85
00:03:27,080 --> 00:03:27,440
space time,

86
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:29,140
but for the moment space

87
00:03:29,140 --> 00:03:30,600
is space and time is time,

88
00:03:30,820 --> 00:03:32,680
and a vector means a thing,

89
00:03:32,840 --> 00:03:34,520
which is a pointer,

90
00:03:34,860 --> 00:03:36,320
and a direction in space,

91
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:37,420
it has a magnitude,

92
00:03:37,720 --> 00:03:39,000
and it has components.

93
00:03:40,200 --> 00:03:42,320
So component by component,

94
00:03:42,360 --> 00:03:44,160
the x component of the force

95
00:03:44,160 --> 00:03:46,480
is equal to the mass of the object

96
00:03:46,480 --> 00:03:48,440
times the x component of acceleration,

97
00:03:49,079 --> 00:03:50,160
y component,

98
00:03:50,160 --> 00:03:50,840
z component,

99
00:03:50,840 --> 00:03:51,760
and so forth.

100
00:03:52,000 --> 00:03:53,490
And in order to indicate

101
00:03:53,490 --> 00:03:54,980
that something is a vector equation,

102
00:03:55,260 --> 00:03:57,060
I'll try to,

103
00:03:57,080 --> 00:04:00,340
I'll try to remember to put an arrow over vectors.

104
00:04:01,080 --> 00:04:02,720
The mass is not a vector.

105
00:04:02,880 --> 00:04:04,420
The mass is simply a number.

106
00:04:04,600 --> 00:04:06,280
Every particle has a mass.

107
00:04:06,460 --> 00:04:07,700
Every object has a mass.

108
00:04:08,260 --> 00:04:10,000
And in Newtonian physics,

109
00:04:10,300 --> 00:04:12,580
the mass is conserved.

110
00:04:12,640 --> 00:04:13,500
It does not change.

111
00:04:13,980 --> 00:04:14,860
Now of course,

112
00:04:14,860 --> 00:04:18,380
the mass of this cup of coffee here can change.

113
00:04:20,740 --> 00:04:21,880
It's lighter now.

114
00:04:22,160 --> 00:04:25,180
But it only changes because mass has been transported

115
00:04:25,180 --> 00:04:26,480
from one place to another

116
00:04:27,640 --> 00:04:29,700
so you can change the mass of an object

117
00:04:29,700 --> 00:04:31,460
by whacking off a piece of it.

118
00:04:31,580 --> 00:04:34,620
But if you don't change the number of particles,

119
00:04:34,800 --> 00:04:35,840
change the number of molecules,

120
00:04:35,840 --> 00:04:36,480
and so forth,

121
00:04:36,680 --> 00:04:39,040
then the mass is a conserved,

122
00:04:39,040 --> 00:04:39,980
unchanging quantity.

123
00:04:40,440 --> 00:04:43,240
So that's the first equation.

124
00:04:43,560 --> 00:04:45,880
Now let me write that in another form.

125
00:04:46,920 --> 00:04:48,060
The other form,

126
00:04:48,140 --> 00:04:50,300
we imagine we have a coordinate system,

127
00:04:50,880 --> 00:04:51,660
an x,

128
00:04:51,660 --> 00:04:51,900
a y,

129
00:04:51,900 --> 00:04:52,380
and a z.

130
00:04:52,760 --> 00:04:55,240
I don't have enough directions on the blackboard

131
00:04:55,240 --> 00:04:55,900
to draw a z.

132
00:04:55,900 --> 00:04:56,560
I won't bother.

133
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:57,560
There's x,

134
00:04:57,560 --> 00:04:58,880
y,

135
00:04:58,880 --> 00:04:59,660
and z.

136
00:05:00,020 --> 00:05:01,780
Sometimes we just call them x1,

137
00:05:01,780 --> 00:05:02,620
x2,

138
00:05:02,620 --> 00:05:04,020
and x3.

139
00:05:04,220 --> 00:05:05,380
I guess I can draw it in.

140
00:05:05,460 --> 00:05:06,580
x3 is over here someplace.

141
00:05:06,920 --> 00:05:07,100
x,

142
00:05:07,100 --> 00:05:07,380
y,

143
00:05:07,380 --> 00:05:07,800
and z.

144
00:05:10,140 --> 00:05:12,960
And a particle has a position,

145
00:05:13,140 --> 00:05:15,180
which means it has a set of three coordinates.

146
00:05:16,760 --> 00:05:18,200
Sometimes we will summarize

147
00:05:18,200 --> 00:05:20,720
the collection of the three coordinates,

148
00:05:22,499 --> 00:05:22,919
x1,

149
00:05:22,919 --> 00:05:23,340
x2,

150
00:05:23,340 --> 00:05:24,100
and x3.

151
00:05:24,420 --> 00:05:24,840
Incidentally,

152
00:05:24,840 --> 00:05:29,180
x1 and x2 and x3 are components of a vector.

153
00:05:29,400 --> 00:05:30,680
The components,

154
00:05:30,680 --> 00:05:31,640
they are components

155
00:05:31,640 --> 00:05:35,120
of the position vector of the particle.

156
00:05:35,840 --> 00:05:38,020
The position vector of the particle

157
00:05:38,840 --> 00:05:42,880
I will often call either small r or large r,

158
00:05:43,840 --> 00:05:47,120
depending on the particular context.

159
00:05:47,620 --> 00:05:49,500
r stands for radius.

160
00:05:49,800 --> 00:05:53,000
But the radius simply means the distance

161
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:54,820
between a point and the origin vector.

162
00:05:54,840 --> 00:05:54,920
So,

163
00:05:54,920 --> 00:05:55,120
for example,

164
00:05:55,820 --> 00:05:58,100
we're really talking now about a thing

165
00:05:58,100 --> 00:05:59,220
with three components,

166
00:05:59,220 --> 00:05:59,800
x,

167
00:05:59,800 --> 00:06:00,100
y,

168
00:06:00,100 --> 00:06:00,440
and z,

169
00:06:00,620 --> 00:06:02,120
and it's the radial vector.

170
00:06:02,340 --> 00:06:03,620
The radial vector,

171
00:06:04,260 --> 00:06:05,940
this is the same thing as

172
00:06:06,740 --> 00:06:10,260
the components of the vector r.

173
00:06:12,520 --> 00:06:13,260
All right.

174
00:06:13,420 --> 00:06:17,160
The acceleration is a vector

175
00:06:17,620 --> 00:06:20,280
that's made up out of the time derivatives

176
00:06:20,280 --> 00:06:21,200
of x,

177
00:06:21,200 --> 00:06:21,620
y,

178
00:06:21,620 --> 00:06:22,220
and z,

179
00:06:22,320 --> 00:06:22,880
or x1,

180
00:06:22,880 --> 00:06:23,260
x2,

181
00:06:23,260 --> 00:06:23,840
and x3.

182
00:06:24,840 --> 00:06:24,840
So,

183
00:06:24,840 --> 00:06:25,720
for each component,

184
00:06:26,020 --> 00:06:26,680
the,

185
00:06:26,680 --> 00:06:29,320
for each component,

186
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:30,300
one,

187
00:06:30,300 --> 00:06:30,560
two,

188
00:06:30,560 --> 00:06:30,960
or three,

189
00:06:31,500 --> 00:06:32,620
the acceleration,

190
00:06:32,980 --> 00:06:34,200
which let me indicate,

191
00:06:34,460 --> 00:06:35,180
well,

192
00:06:35,180 --> 00:06:36,400
let's just call it a,

193
00:06:36,640 --> 00:06:39,780
the acceleration is just equal,

194
00:06:40,060 --> 00:06:41,520
the components of it,

195
00:06:41,600 --> 00:06:45,100
are equal to the second derivatives

196
00:06:45,100 --> 00:06:48,340
of the coordinates with respect to time.

197
00:06:50,640 --> 00:06:52,200
That's what acceleration is.

198
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:54,120
The first derivative

199
00:06:54,840 --> 00:06:56,800
of position is called velocity.

200
00:07:02,400 --> 00:07:04,720
We can take this to be component by component,

201
00:07:04,940 --> 00:07:05,400
x1,

202
00:07:05,400 --> 00:07:05,780
x2,

203
00:07:05,780 --> 00:07:06,360
and x3.

204
00:07:06,540 --> 00:07:08,160
The first derivative is velocity.

205
00:07:08,440 --> 00:07:10,020
The second derivative is acceleration.

206
00:07:11,540 --> 00:07:13,320
We can write this in vector notation.

207
00:07:13,720 --> 00:07:14,300
I won't bother.

208
00:07:14,980 --> 00:07:16,420
But we all know what we mean.

209
00:07:16,660 --> 00:07:18,400
I hope we all know what we mean

210
00:07:18,400 --> 00:07:18,900
by these,

211
00:07:18,900 --> 00:07:20,680
by acceleration and velocity.

212
00:07:21,180 --> 00:07:21,880
And so,

213
00:07:21,880 --> 00:07:24,340
Newton's equations are then summarized

214
00:07:24,840 --> 00:07:25,680
not summarized,

215
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:26,280
but rewritten

216
00:07:26,840 --> 00:07:28,740
as the force on an object,

217
00:07:28,940 --> 00:07:29,720
whatever it is,

218
00:07:29,820 --> 00:07:31,900
component by component

219
00:07:32,740 --> 00:07:34,000
is equal to the mass

220
00:07:34,780 --> 00:07:36,120
times the second derivative

221
00:07:36,840 --> 00:07:38,780
of the component of position.

222
00:07:40,260 --> 00:07:42,100
So that's the summary of,

223
00:07:42,220 --> 00:07:44,140
I think it's Newton's first and second law.

224
00:07:44,220 --> 00:07:45,520
I can never remember which they are.

225
00:07:47,780 --> 00:07:48,760
Newton's first law,

226
00:07:48,760 --> 00:07:49,160
of course,

227
00:07:49,360 --> 00:07:52,380
is simply the statement that if there are no forces,

228
00:07:53,460 --> 00:07:55,100
then there's no acceleration.

229
00:07:55,680 --> 00:07:56,960
That's Newton's first law.

230
00:07:57,180 --> 00:07:59,000
That's the second law.

231
00:07:59,180 --> 00:08:00,480
Third law is equal and opposite.

232
00:08:00,480 --> 00:08:01,080
Equal and opposite,

233
00:08:01,080 --> 00:08:01,400
right.

234
00:08:02,740 --> 00:08:05,580
So this summarizes both the first and second law.

235
00:08:06,640 --> 00:08:08,010
I never understood why there

236
00:08:08,010 --> 00:08:09,380
was a first and second law.

237
00:08:09,480 --> 00:08:10,520
It seemed to me there was just one,

238
00:08:10,520 --> 00:08:11,300
F equals m a.

239
00:08:12,600 --> 00:08:13,320
All right,

240
00:08:13,320 --> 00:08:13,860
now,

241
00:08:15,040 --> 00:08:18,340
let's begin even previous to Newton

242
00:08:18,340 --> 00:08:20,700
with Galilean gravity.

243
00:08:20,700 --> 00:08:24,140
Gravity as Galileo understood it.

244
00:08:24,640 --> 00:08:25,200
Actually,

245
00:08:25,200 --> 00:08:27,180
I'm not sure how much of this mathematics

246
00:08:27,180 --> 00:08:28,980
Galileo did or didn't understand.

247
00:08:30,120 --> 00:08:31,919
He certainly knew what acceleration was.

248
00:08:32,419 --> 00:08:33,140
He measured it.

249
00:08:35,080 --> 00:08:36,880
I don't know that he had the...

250
00:08:36,880 --> 00:08:38,100
He certainly didn't have calculus,

251
00:08:38,200 --> 00:08:39,659
but he knew what acceleration was.

252
00:08:40,080 --> 00:08:44,760
So what Galileo studied was the motion of objects

253
00:08:44,760 --> 00:08:46,900
in the gravitational field of the Earth

254
00:08:46,900 --> 00:08:50,680
in the approximation that the Earth is moving.

255
00:08:50,680 --> 00:08:51,000
The Earth is flat.

256
00:08:51,280 --> 00:08:51,540
Now,

257
00:08:51,540 --> 00:08:53,080
Galileo knew the Earth wasn't flat.

258
00:08:53,860 --> 00:08:57,780
But he studied gravity in the approximation

259
00:08:57,780 --> 00:08:59,420
where you never moved very far

260
00:08:59,420 --> 00:09:01,060
from the surface of the Earth.

261
00:09:01,500 --> 00:09:02,720
And if you don't move very

262
00:09:02,720 --> 00:09:03,940
far from the surface of the Earth,

263
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:04,990
you might as well take the

264
00:09:04,990 --> 00:09:05,980
surface of the Earth to be flat.

265
00:09:06,660 --> 00:09:09,500
And the significance of that is twofold.

266
00:09:10,080 --> 00:09:11,020
First of all,

267
00:09:11,020 --> 00:09:13,140
the direction of gravitational forces

268
00:09:13,140 --> 00:09:14,860
is the same everywheres.

269
00:09:15,220 --> 00:09:16,260
This is not true,

270
00:09:16,260 --> 00:09:16,720
of course,

271
00:09:16,720 --> 00:09:17,620
if the Earth is curved.

272
00:09:18,900 --> 00:09:20,660
Then gravity will point to the Earth.

273
00:09:20,680 --> 00:09:21,240
Toward the center.

274
00:09:21,620 --> 00:09:23,680
But in the flat space approximation,

275
00:09:24,160 --> 00:09:25,740
gravity points down.

276
00:09:26,440 --> 00:09:29,000
Down everywhere is always in the same direction.

277
00:09:29,520 --> 00:09:30,640
And second of all,

278
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:32,460
perhaps a little bit less obvious,

279
00:09:32,500 --> 00:09:33,540
but nevertheless true,

280
00:09:33,820 --> 00:09:37,860
in the approximation where the Earth is infinite and flat,

281
00:09:38,420 --> 00:09:39,620
goes on and on forever,

282
00:09:39,620 --> 00:09:40,840
infinite and flat,

283
00:09:41,480 --> 00:09:44,980
the gravitational force doesn't depend on how high you are.

284
00:09:45,140 --> 00:09:47,680
Same gravitational force here as here.

285
00:09:48,080 --> 00:09:49,680
The implication of that

286
00:09:50,680 --> 00:09:52,820
is that the acceleration of gravity,

287
00:09:53,380 --> 00:09:54,500
since force,

288
00:09:54,500 --> 00:09:56,800
apart from the mass of an object,

289
00:09:57,020 --> 00:09:58,480
the acceleration on an object,

290
00:09:58,720 --> 00:10:00,680
is independent of where you put it.

291
00:10:01,880 --> 00:10:03,000
And so,

292
00:10:04,800 --> 00:10:05,360
Galileo

293
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:08,440
either did or didn't realize,

294
00:10:09,740 --> 00:10:10,300
well,

295
00:10:10,300 --> 00:10:10,520
he,

296
00:10:12,120 --> 00:10:12,680
again,

297
00:10:12,680 --> 00:10:15,260
I don't know exactly what Galileo did or didn't know,

298
00:10:15,360 --> 00:10:17,560
but what he said was equivalent to saying

299
00:10:17,560 --> 00:10:21,340
that the force on an object

300
00:10:21,340 --> 00:10:23,420
in the flat space approximation

301
00:10:24,140 --> 00:10:25,420
is very simple.

302
00:10:25,560 --> 00:10:28,420
It's first of all has only one component pointing downward.

303
00:10:29,820 --> 00:10:32,000
If we take the upward

304
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:34,180
sense of things to be positive,

305
00:10:35,020 --> 00:10:37,740
then we would say that the force is,

306
00:10:38,620 --> 00:10:40,960
let's just say the component of the force

307
00:10:41,560 --> 00:10:43,800
in the x2 direction,

308
00:10:44,020 --> 00:10:45,220
the vertical direction,

309
00:10:45,220 --> 00:10:47,420
is equal to minus,

310
00:10:47,660 --> 00:10:50,140
the minus simply means that the force is downward,

311
00:10:51,620 --> 00:10:55,260
and it's proportional to the mass of the object

312
00:10:55,940 --> 00:11:00,220
