divided by the square of the distance between them,

1160
00:40:03,617 --> 00:40:04,957
let's call that r i j,

1161
00:40:05,977 --> 00:40:06,497
squared.

1162
00:40:08,457 --> 00:40:11,717
The distance between the i-th particle is i and j,

1163
00:40:11,917 --> 00:40:13,677
the distance between the i-th particle

1164
00:40:13,677 --> 00:40:15,597
and the j-th particle is r i j.

1165
00:40:17,417 --> 00:40:18,337
But then,

1166
00:40:19,037 --> 00:40:20,817
just as we did before,

1167
00:40:21,017 --> 00:40:22,517
we have to give it a direction.

1168
00:40:23,157 --> 00:40:24,777
Put a minus sign here,

1169
00:40:24,917 --> 00:40:26,237
that indicates that it's attractive.

1170
00:40:27,157 --> 00:40:29,377
Another r i j upstairs,

1171
00:40:29,697 --> 00:40:31,637
but that's a vector r i j,

1172
00:40:31,837 --> 00:40:33,497
and make this cube downstairs.

1173
00:40:34,797 --> 00:40:35,357
Alright,

1174
00:40:35,357 --> 00:40:36,217
so that says

1175
00:40:36,217 --> 00:40:38,617
that the force on the i-th particle

1176
00:40:38,617 --> 00:40:40,957
is the sum of all the forces

1177
00:40:40,957 --> 00:40:42,257
due to all the other ones

1178
00:40:43,237 --> 00:40:45,497
of the product of their masses,

1179
00:40:46,877 --> 00:40:48,317
inverse square in the distance,

1180
00:40:48,337 --> 00:40:48,517
and the denominator,

1181
00:40:48,977 --> 00:40:52,497
and the direction of each individual force

1182
00:40:52,497 --> 00:40:53,677
on this particle,

1183
00:40:53,817 --> 00:40:55,057
is toward the other.

1184
00:40:56,497 --> 00:40:57,057
Alright,

1185
00:40:57,057 --> 00:40:58,017
this is a vector sum.

1186
00:40:58,477 --> 00:40:58,937
Yeah?

1187
00:41:00,197 --> 00:41:03,037
The minus indicates that it's attractive.

1188
00:41:05,197 --> 00:41:05,757
Oh,

1189
00:41:05,757 --> 00:41:06,317
excellent.

1190
00:41:06,737 --> 00:41:09,137
But you've got the vector going from i to j.

1191
00:41:10,617 --> 00:41:11,177
Oh.

1192
00:41:12,917 --> 00:41:13,477
Uh...

1193
00:41:16,217 --> 00:41:16,917
Let's see.

1194
00:41:20,057 --> 00:41:22,297
That's a vector going from r to i to j.

1195
00:41:22,397 --> 00:41:22,577
Yes,

1196
00:41:22,577 --> 00:41:23,777
there is a question of the sign

1197
00:41:23,777 --> 00:41:25,237
of this vector over here.

1198
00:41:26,297 --> 00:41:26,697
So,

1199
00:41:26,697 --> 00:41:27,097
yeah,

1200
00:41:27,097 --> 00:41:28,257
you're absolutely...

1201
00:41:28,937 --> 00:41:29,737
Let's see.

1202
00:41:30,337 --> 00:41:30,737
Blah,

1203
00:41:30,737 --> 00:41:30,837
blah,

1204
00:41:30,837 --> 00:41:30,997
blah,

1205
00:41:30,997 --> 00:41:31,137
blah,

1206
00:41:31,137 --> 00:41:31,217
blah.

1207
00:41:32,717 --> 00:41:33,117
Um...

1208
00:41:35,277 --> 00:41:35,677
Yeah.

1209
00:41:35,957 --> 00:41:37,217
I actually think it's...

1210
00:41:37,217 --> 00:41:37,577
Yeah,

1211
00:41:37,577 --> 00:41:37,997
you're right.

1212
00:41:38,117 --> 00:41:39,117
You're absolutely right.

1213
00:41:39,257 --> 00:41:40,217
The way I've written it,

1214
00:41:40,237 --> 00:41:42,057
there should not be a minus sign here.

1215
00:41:43,277 --> 00:41:43,677
Alright?

1216
00:41:43,757 --> 00:41:45,537
But if I put r j i there,

1217
00:41:46,737 --> 00:41:48,097
then there would be a minus sign.

1218
00:41:48,337 --> 00:41:48,417
Alright?

1219
00:41:49,437 --> 00:41:50,317
So you're right.

1220
00:41:51,657 --> 00:41:52,137
Uh...

1221
00:41:53,937 --> 00:41:55,397
But in any case,

1222
00:41:55,457 --> 00:41:58,277
every one of the forces is attractive.

1223
00:41:59,897 --> 00:42:00,377
Alright?

1224
00:42:00,977 --> 00:42:02,247
And what we have to

1225
00:42:02,247 --> 00:42:03,517
do is to add them up.

1226
00:42:03,697 --> 00:42:05,517
We have to add them up as vectors.

1227
00:42:05,777 --> 00:42:07,657
And so there's some resulting vector,

1228
00:42:07,897 --> 00:42:09,057
some resultant vector,

1229
00:42:09,637 --> 00:42:12,337
which doesn't point toward any one of them in particular,

1230
00:42:12,857 --> 00:42:14,457
but points in some direction,

1231
00:42:14,577 --> 00:42:16,057
which is determined by the

1232
00:42:16,057 --> 00:42:17,537
vector sum of all the others.

1233
00:42:18,337 --> 00:42:18,657
Alright?

1234
00:42:18,817 --> 00:42:21,857
But the interesting fact is,

1235
00:42:21,937 --> 00:42:23,357
if we combine this...

1236
00:42:23,357 --> 00:42:25,397
This is the force on the i-th particle.

1237
00:42:25,677 --> 00:42:28,217
If we combine it with Newton's equations...

1238
00:42:28,217 --> 00:42:29,417
Let's combine it with Newton's...

1239
00:42:29,417 --> 00:42:33,597
with Newton's f equals m a equations,

1240
00:42:35,017 --> 00:42:35,497
then...

1241
00:42:40,757 --> 00:42:41,237
Well,

1242
00:42:41,237 --> 00:42:41,857
this is f.

1243
00:42:46,217 --> 00:42:46,697
This...

1244
00:42:46,697 --> 00:42:47,697
On the i-th particle,

1245
00:42:47,697 --> 00:42:50,557
this is equal to the mass of the i-th particle

1246
00:42:51,017 --> 00:42:53,217
times the acceleration of the i-th particle.

1247
00:42:53,457 --> 00:42:53,917
Again,

1248
00:42:53,917 --> 00:42:54,957
vector equations.

1249
00:42:56,497 --> 00:42:56,957
Now,

1250
00:42:56,957 --> 00:43:00,537
the sum here is over all the other particles.

1251
00:43:02,057 --> 00:43:03,777
We're focusing on number i.

1252
00:43:05,957 --> 00:43:06,417
i,

1253
00:43:06,417 --> 00:43:08,097
the mass of the i-th particle,

1254
00:43:08,197 --> 00:43:09,597
will cancel out of this equation.

1255
00:43:10,017 --> 00:43:11,317
I don't want to throw it away,

1256
00:43:11,437 --> 00:43:13,157
but let's just circle it

1257
00:43:13,667 --> 00:43:15,057
and now put it over on the side.

1258
00:43:17,697 --> 00:43:19,837
We notice that the acceleration

1259
00:43:20,317 --> 00:43:21,517
of the i-th particle

1260
00:43:21,517 --> 00:43:23,657
does not depend on its mass again.

1261
00:43:24,077 --> 00:43:24,857
Once again,

1262
00:43:24,857 --> 00:43:26,657
because the mass occurs

1263
00:43:26,657 --> 00:43:28,357
in both sides of the equation,

1264
00:43:28,477 --> 00:43:29,497
it can be canceled out,

1265
00:43:29,597 --> 00:43:31,637
and the motion of the i-th particle

1266
00:43:31,637 --> 00:43:35,177
does not depend on the mass of the i-th particle.

1267
00:43:35,237 --> 00:43:37,257
It depends on the masses of all the other ones.

1268
00:43:38,557 --> 00:43:39,937
All the other ones come in,

1269
00:43:39,977 --> 00:43:41,557
but the mass of the i-th particle

1270
00:43:42,097 --> 00:43:43,277
cancels out of the equation.

1271
00:43:43,757 --> 00:43:44,777
So what that means

1272
00:43:44,777 --> 00:43:47,597
is if we had a whole bunch of particles,

1273
00:43:47,597 --> 00:43:47,837
here,

1274
00:43:49,277 --> 00:43:51,557
and we added one more over here,

1275
00:43:52,217 --> 00:43:54,877
its motion would not depend

1276
00:43:54,877 --> 00:43:56,277
on the mass of that particle.

1277
00:43:56,377 --> 00:43:58,357
It depends on the mass of all the other ones,

1278
00:43:58,497 --> 00:44:00,057
but it doesn't depend on the mass

1279
00:44:00,057 --> 00:44:01,097
of the i-th particle here.

1280
00:44:02,677 --> 00:44:03,197
That's,

1281
00:44:03,197 --> 00:44:03,717
again,

1282
00:44:03,717 --> 00:44:05,077
the equivalence principle,

1283
00:44:05,237 --> 00:44:08,477
that the motion of a particle

1284
00:44:08,477 --> 00:44:10,077
doesn't depend on its mass.

1285
00:44:10,477 --> 00:44:11,237
And again,

1286
00:44:11,237 --> 00:44:13,917
if we had a whole bunch of particles here,

1287
00:44:14,897 --> 00:44:16,477
if they were close enough together,

1288
00:44:16,477 --> 00:44:18,837
they would all move in the same way.

1289
00:44:20,377 --> 00:44:24,597
Before I discuss a little more mathematics,

1290
00:44:26,097 --> 00:44:27,917
let's just discuss tidal forces,

1291
00:44:28,117 --> 00:44:29,497
what tidal forces are.

1292
00:44:29,677 --> 00:44:31,337
Can I ask one question?

1293
00:44:31,517 --> 00:44:31,557
Yeah.

1294
00:44:33,077 --> 00:44:35,797
Once you set this whole thing into motion,

1295
00:44:35,857 --> 00:44:36,397
dynamically,

1296
00:44:37,217 --> 00:44:38,857
we have all different masses,

1297
00:44:39,317 --> 00:44:41,557
and each particle is going to be affected

1298
00:44:41,557 --> 00:44:42,957
by each one differently.

1299
00:44:43,257 --> 00:44:43,277
Yes,

1300
00:44:43,277 --> 00:44:43,337
yes,

1301
00:44:43,337 --> 00:44:43,557
yes.

1302
00:44:44,617 --> 00:44:46,137
I think I know what you're going to ask,

1303
00:44:46,137 --> 00:44:46,457
but I'm just...

1304
00:44:46,457 --> 00:44:48,997
Every particle in there is going to experience

1305
00:44:48,997 --> 00:44:51,077
a uniform acceleration?

1306
00:44:51,497 --> 00:44:51,717
No,

1307
00:44:51,717 --> 00:44:51,817
no,

1308
00:44:51,817 --> 00:44:51,937
no.

1309
00:44:52,477 --> 00:44:55,437
The acceleration is not uniform.

1310
00:44:56,267 --> 00:44:58,817
The acceleration will get larger

1311
00:44:58,817 --> 00:45:01,317
when it gets closer to one of the particles.

1312
00:45:06,017 --> 00:45:08,337
It won't be uniform anymore.

1313
00:45:08,757 --> 00:45:11,417
It won't be uniform now because the force

1314
00:45:12,127 --> 00:45:14,277
is not independent of where you are.

1315
00:45:14,277 --> 00:45:17,217
Now the force depends on where you are

1316
00:45:17,217 --> 00:45:19,797
relative to the objects that are exerting the force.

1317
00:45:19,997 --> 00:45:22,017
It was only in the flat Earth approximation

1318
00:45:23,057 --> 00:45:25,357
where the force didn't depend on where you were.

1319
00:45:26,577 --> 00:45:27,137
Okay?

1320
00:45:28,057 --> 00:45:30,057
Now the force varies,

1321
00:45:30,177 --> 00:45:32,717
so it's larger when you're far away,

1322
00:45:33,437 --> 00:45:33,997
it's...sorry,

1323
00:45:33,997 --> 00:45:35,957
it's smaller when you're far away,

1324
00:45:36,137 --> 00:45:37,637
it's larger when you're in close.

1325
00:45:38,557 --> 00:45:39,117
Okay?

1326
00:45:39,637 --> 00:45:42,897
But is it going to be changing in a...

1327
00:45:44,317 --> 00:45:47,977
It changes in a vector form

1328
00:45:47,977 --> 00:45:51,717
with each individual particle.

1329
00:45:51,837 --> 00:45:53,417
Each one of them is changing position.

1330
00:45:53,757 --> 00:45:54,017
Yeah.

1331
00:45:54,677 --> 00:45:58,257
And so is the dynamics that every one of them

1332
00:45:58,257 --> 00:46:00,477
is going towards the center of gravity

1333
00:46:00,477 --> 00:46:01,277
of the entire...

1334
00:46:01,857 --> 00:46:02,677
Not necessarily.

1335
00:46:02,917 --> 00:46:03,577
I mean,

1336
00:46:03,577 --> 00:46:05,237
they could be flying apart from each other,

1337
00:46:05,297 --> 00:46:07,377
but they will be accelerating toward each other.

1338
00:46:08,317 --> 00:46:08,797
Okay?

1339
00:46:08,877 --> 00:46:10,817
If I throw this eraser into the air

1340
00:46:10,817 --> 00:46:12,157
with greater than the escape velocity,

1341
00:46:12,517 --> 00:46:14,257
it's not going to turn around and fall back down.

1342
00:46:15,537 --> 00:46:16,117
No,

1343
00:46:16,117 --> 00:46:16,837
the question is,

1344
00:46:16,857 --> 00:46:18,797
is the acceleration a uniform acceleration

1345
00:46:18,797 --> 00:46:21,337
or is it a changing dynamic acceleration?

1346
00:46:21,577 --> 00:46:22,337
Changing with what?

1347
00:46:22,377 --> 00:46:23,217
With respect to what?

1348
00:46:23,317 --> 00:46:23,817
Time?

1349
00:46:24,337 --> 00:46:24,917
Oh,

1350
00:46:24,917 --> 00:46:26,517
it changes with respect to time

1351
00:46:26,517 --> 00:46:29,417
because the object moves further and further away.

1352
00:46:29,777 --> 00:46:33,317
In the two-mass system,

1353
00:46:35,117 --> 00:46:37,517
I call that a uniform acceleration.

1354
00:46:38,817 --> 00:46:40,837
Uniform with respect to what?

1355
00:46:42,037 --> 00:46:43,077
It's not uniform.

1356
00:46:43,137 --> 00:46:44,237
The radius is...

1357
00:46:44,257 --> 00:46:44,537
The radius is changing

1358
00:46:44,537 --> 00:46:47,177
and it's inverse cubed with the radius.

1359
00:46:47,397 --> 00:46:48,137
Inverse squared.

1360
00:46:51,137 --> 00:46:52,557
One of these can't...

1361
00:46:52,557 --> 00:46:53,037
Inverse squared.

1362
00:46:53,617 --> 00:46:54,137
Yeah.

1363
00:46:54,317 --> 00:46:55,237
Let's take the Earth.

1364
00:46:55,317 --> 00:46:55,797
Here's the Earth

1365
00:46:55,797 --> 00:46:58,977
and we drop a small mass from far away.

1366
00:46:59,477 --> 00:47:01,177
As that mass moves in,

1367
00:47:01,357 --> 00:47:02,917
its acceleration increases.

1368
00:47:03,337 --> 00:47:04,777
Why does its acceleration increase?

1369
00:47:04,997 --> 00:47:06,237
Its acceleration increases

1370
00:47:06,237 --> 00:47:08,797
because the radial distance gets smaller.

1371
00:47:09,337 --> 00:47:10,417
So in that sense,

1372
00:47:10,417 --> 00:47:11,397
it's not the...

1373
00:47:11,397 --> 00:47:12,997
All right.

1374
00:47:13,017 --> 00:47:13,137
Now,

1375
00:47:13,137 --> 00:47:17,637
once the gravitational force depends on distance,

1376
00:47:18,757 --> 00:47:21,797
then it's not really quite true

1377
00:47:21,797 --> 00:47:25,617
that you don't feel anything in a gravitational field.

1378
00:47:25,797 --> 00:47:28,417
You feel something which is to some extent different

1379
00:47:28,417 --> 00:47:32,737
than you would feel in free space

1380
00:47:32,737 --> 00:47:34,737
without any gravitational field.

1381
00:47:34,977 --> 00:47:37,897
The reason is more or less obvious.

1382
00:47:39,057 --> 00:47:40,337
Here you are.

1383
00:47:40,457 --> 00:47:40,857
Here's...

1384
00:47:41,597 --> 00:47:42,577
Here's the Earth.

1385
00:47:44,257 --> 00:47:44,857
Now,

1386
00:47:44,857 --> 00:47:47,317
you or me or whoever it is

1387
00:47:47,317 --> 00:47:49,297
happens to be extremely tall.

1388
00:47:55,477 --> 00:47:57,637
A couple of thousand miles tall.

1389
00:47:59,477 --> 00:48:00,077
Well,

1390
00:48:00,077 --> 00:48:03,077
this person's feet are being pulled

1391
00:48:03,077 --> 00:48:06,497
by the gravitational field more than his head.

1392
00:48:06,617 --> 00:48:08,897
Or another way of saying the same thing is...

1393
00:48:08,897 --> 00:48:10,837
Let's imagine that the person is...

1394
00:48:10,837 --> 00:48:12,617
This person is very loosely held together.

1395
00:48:12,977 --> 00:48:15,877
He's just more or less a gas of a...

1396
00:48:17,577 --> 00:48:19,417
We are pretty loosely held together.

1397
00:48:19,617 --> 00:48:20,197
At least I am.

1398
00:48:21,077 --> 00:48:21,637
Right.

1399
00:48:22,137 --> 00:48:22,857
All right.

1400
00:48:24,197 --> 00:48:28,977
The acceleration on the lower portions of his body

1401
00:48:28,977 --> 00:48:31,517
are larger than the accelerations

1402
00:48:31,517 --> 00:48:33,297
on the upper portions of his body.

1403
00:48:33,477 --> 00:48:35,257
So it's quite clear what happens to him.

1404
00:48:35,337 --> 00:48:36,137
He gets stretched.

1405
00:48:36,517 --> 00:48:40,177
He doesn't get a sense of falling as such.

1406
00:48:40,177 --> 00:48:41,837
He gets a sense of stretching,

1407
00:48:41,837 --> 00:48:42,997
being stretched.

1408
00:48:43,717 --> 00:48:45,657
Feet being pulled away from his head.

1409
00:48:46,477 --> 00:48:47,877
At the same time,

1410
00:48:47,877 --> 00:48:48,517
let's...

1411
00:48:48,517 --> 00:48:49,477
All right.

1412
00:48:49,497 --> 00:48:49,837
So...

1413
00:48:54,397 --> 00:48:56,377
Let's change his shape a little bit.

1414
00:49:00,777 --> 00:49:02,337
I just spent a week,

1415
00:49:02,337 --> 00:49:03,217
two weeks in Italy,

1416
00:49:03,337 --> 00:49:05,357
and my shape changes whenever I go to Italy,

1417
00:49:05,517 --> 00:49:06,857
and it tends to get more horizontal.

1418
00:49:06,977 --> 00:49:07,877
My head is here.

1419
00:49:08,317 --> 00:49:09,397
My feet are here.

1420
00:49:10,177 --> 00:49:11,117
And now I'm this way.

1421
00:49:12,357 --> 00:49:13,837
Still loosely put together.

1422
00:49:14,497 --> 00:49:15,157
All right.

1423
00:49:15,857 --> 00:49:16,617
Now what?

1424
00:49:17,117 --> 00:49:17,617
Well,

1425
00:49:17,617 --> 00:49:21,137
not only does the force depend on the distance,

1426
00:49:21,297 --> 00:49:22,917
but it also depends on the direction.

1427
00:49:23,517 --> 00:49:26,567
The force on my left

1428
00:49:26,567 --> 00:49:29,617
end over here is this way.

1429
00:49:29,977 --> 00:49:31,267
The force on my right

1430
00:49:31,267 --> 00:49:32,557
end over here is this way.

1431
00:49:33,557 --> 00:49:35,997
The force on the top of my head is down,

1432
00:49:36,177 --> 00:49:38,497
but it's weaker than the force on my feet.

1433
00:49:39,417 --> 00:49:40,837
So there are two effects.

1434
00:49:41,457 --> 00:49:44,437
One effect is to stretch me vertically.

1435
00:49:45,097 --> 00:49:46,497
It's because my head is not

1436
00:49:46,497 --> 00:49:47,897
being pulled as hard as my feet.

1437
00:49:48,257 --> 00:49:51,597
But the other effect is to be squished horizontally

1438
00:49:52,297 --> 00:49:54,237
by the fact that the forces

1439
00:49:54,237 --> 00:49:56,177
on the left end of me

1440
00:49:56,177 --> 00:49:58,057
are pointing slightly to the right,

1441
00:49:58,197 --> 00:50:00,317
and the forces on the right end of me

1442
00:50:00,317 --> 00:50:01,757
are pointing slightly to the left.

1443
00:50:02,057 --> 00:50:04,837
So a loosely knit person like this,

1444
00:50:05,877 --> 00:50:08,477
falling in free fall near the ground,

1445
00:50:08,497 --> 00:50:11,457
a real planet or a real gravitational object

1446
00:50:11,457 --> 00:50:15,237
which has a real Newtonian gravitational field around it,

1447
00:50:15,337 --> 00:50:18,617
will experience a distortion,

1448
00:50:19,057 --> 00:50:21,597
will experience a degree of distortion

1449
00:50:21,597 --> 00:50:24,937
and a degree of being stretched vertically,

1450
00:50:25,177 --> 00:50:26,557
being compressed horizontally.

1451
00:50:29,037 --> 00:50:32,517
But if the object is small enough,

1452
00:50:34,577 --> 00:50:36,237
what does small enough mean?

1453
00:50:36,377 --> 00:50:37,997
Let's suppose the object that's falling

1454
00:50:37,997 --> 00:50:38,817
